crowdsourced_yara_results.description: This signature detects the presence of a number of Windows API functionality often seen within embedded executables. When this signature alerts on an executable, it is not an indication of malicious behavior. However, if seen firing in other file types, deeper investigation may be warranted.
crowdsourced_yara_results.author: InQuest Labs

attributes.magic: ELF 32-bit LSB executable, ARM, EABI5 version 1 (SYSV), dynamically linked, interpreter /lib/ld-linux-armhf.so.3, BuildID[sha1]=70fc913017d3c96ba13f58edf1a8b29b3b3469d8, for GNU/Linux 3.2.0, stripped

threat_severity.level_description: Severity HIGH because it was considered trojan. Other contributing factor was that it could not be run in sandboxes.

crowdsourced_ai_results.analysis: The binary is a legitimate, albeit customized, OpenSSH server daemon (sshd version 7.4p1) compiled for an ARM-based embedded device, likely from Sigmastar. It parses standard sshd command-line arguments, handles SSH connections, authentication, and session management. It contains numerous strings and references to files standard for sshd, such as `/usr/local/etc/sshd_config`, `~/.ssh/authorized_keys`, and `/var/run/sshd.pid`. The binary also includes vendor-specific customizations for handling device configuration from paths like `/mnt/mtd/Config/deviceInfo` and `/usr/etc/telnet_cfg`, which is common for embedded systems. There are no indicators of malicious behavior.
